  "nursesNote": "A crisis is an acute, time-limited state (usually resolving in about 4 to 6 weeks) that occurs when a person's usual coping is overwhelmed; anyone can experience one. Types include maturational (developmental changes like marriage or retirement), situational (external events like job loss or illness), and adventitious (disasters or violence). The nurse first ensures safety by assessing risk of harm to self or others, then stays focused on the immediate here-and-now problem rather than deep insight work. Crisis intervention is short-term, active, and directive: the nurse helps the patient solve the present problem, strengthen coping, and mobilize support, with the goal of returning to at least the pre-crisis level of functioning.",
